Your nested listener constantly clear `UserList` for each user it finds:

    UserList.clear();
    User user = snapshot.getValue(User.class);
    String a = user.getUserID();

    UserList.add(user);

After you do this for all users, you end up with a list that just contains the last user.

In general your code seems off though, as you&#39;re loading all users, for each trip that you load. Worse: you use `addValueListener`, which means that if any user is changed, you&#39;re reloading all of them for each trip. That&#39;s not only incredibly wasteful, but also probably incorrect.

More typical/idiomatic is to only load the user for each trip (so one level lower in the JSON tree), and to use `addListenerForSingleValueEvent` (which will load the data once, and then stop listening).

So something like:


    DatabaseReference UserRef = database.getReference().child(&quot;User&quot;).child(userID);
    UserRef.addValueEventListener(new ValueEventListener() {
        @Override
        public void onDataChange(@NonNull DataSnapshot dataSnapshot) {
            if (dataSnapshot.exists()){
                User user = snapshot.getValue(User.class);
                String a = user.getUserID();

                UserList.add(user);

                Log.d(TAG, &quot;2ìœ ì €ë¦¬í¼â˜…who    &quot;+a);
            }
            tripSearchAdapter2.notifyDataSetChanged();
        }

        @Override
        public void onCancelled(@NonNull DatabaseError databaseError) {
            throw databaseError.toException();
        }
    });

The changes between your code and this:

* Pass in `userID` to the `UserRef` path, so that you&#39;re only loading the data for the user of the current trip.
* Remove the `for(DataSnapshot snapshot: dataSnapshot.getChildren())` as we&#39;re only loading a single user.
* Remove the `String who = dataSnapshot.child(&quot;userID&quot;).getValue().toString()`, since you already have the same value in `userID`.
* Remove `UserList.clear();`, since otherwise you&#39;re clearing the user list after every user that you load.
* Implement your `onCancelled`, because ignoring errors is never a good idea.

